\begin{abstract}
A four-dimensional ($4\text{D}$) fast--slow dynamical system for the nocturnal stable boundary layer (SBL) is developed using Geometric Singular Perturbation Theory (GSPT). The model couples fast turbulent kinetic energy (TKE) evolution with slow atmospheric rotational dynamics and surface thermodynamic variables, analyzed through its critical-manifold geometry and reduced-layer decomposition. By introducing nonlinear Kolmogorov dissipation and a local Lipschitz activation gate ($\sqrt{e+\delta}$) in the fast subsystem, we demonstrate that regime transitions are governed by a non-degenerate fold catastrophe coupled with a transversal boundary recovery mechanism near $e = 0$. Compact, normally hyperbolic subsets of the constraint set organize the slow flow, while turbulence collapse and breakout thresholds map directly to forcing diagnostics tied to shear-stratification competition. Eddy diffusivities are parameterized as prognostic functions of TKE, yielding reduced slow dynamics on the slow equilibrium manifold in the singular limit $\varepsilon \to 0$. The governing equations naturally reproduce Blackadar-type inertial oscillations during frictional decoupling without phenomenological prescription. This formulation generalizes classical $1.5$-order TKE models by replacing instantaneous equilibrium assumptions with explicit fast--slow manifold dynamics, thereby distinguishing the framework from both conventional prognostic TKE transport closures and algebraic equilibrium closures. The framework provides a first-principles geometric interpretation of SBL regime transitions across stability regimes; \texttt{\{\{dataset\}\}} is utilized as the primary baseline dataset for generated diagnostics, regime maps, and comparative sensitivity envelopes.
\end{abstract}